		<td class="row2" width="100%" height="28" valign="top"><table width="100%" border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0">
			<tr>
				<td width="100%"><a href="viewtopic.php?p=53165&amp;sid=0b122fa4bd4aaec254fd09943077e859#53165"><img src="templates/myth2/images/icon_minipost.gif" width="12" height="9" alt="Post" title="Post" border="0" /></a><span class="postdetails">Posted: Sat Nov 06, 2004 5:46 pm<span class="gen">&nbsp;</span>&nbsp; &nbsp;Post subject:                                                             </span></td>
				<td valign="top" align="right" nowrap="nowrap"><a href="posting.php?mode=quote&amp;p=53165&amp;sid=0b122fa4bd4aaec254fd09943077e859"><img src="templates/myth2/images/lang_english/icon_quote.gif" alt="Reply with quote" title="Reply with quote" border="0" /></a>   </td>
			</tr>
			<tr>
				<td colspan="2"><hr /></td>
			</tr>
			<tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">The figure was lithe and agile, slipping in and out of shadows so effortlessly one might assume he had only imagined her. She had learned quickly to be stealthy and cunning, one must be more deadly than one’s allies when dealing with the wicked tier’dal. Wicked but fascinating… She had made Neriak her home many seasons ago, when she was still but a child in the eyes of many, barely old enough to control many of the majiks a rogue can call her own. At first she had used deceit to gain acceptance, masquerading as one of them, only confident when she took the exotic form of these dark elves. The romance of them had worn off quickly of course. When surrounded by the brutality and backstabbing that is tier’dal society, one can not look through starry eyes, not if you wanted to survive. In a society that thrives on hate, violence and deception, the true survivors learn to see things for what they are, and to look below the surface on everything. So no, she no longer found the tier’dal mysterious and romantic… but they were still beautiful. Even in their intrigues and bloodlust there was a certain macabre grace. 
<br />

<br />
She slid silently in through an open window, high above the city streets. As usual, Tani left the assassinations within the city to the dobluth, the outsider, his tier’dal agents preferring to at least adhere to the Commandments in body if not in spirit. It was forbidden for one tier’dal to raise swords against another. The crafty dark elves used allies such as Shaddowe to get around such inconvenient laws, knowing full well that though their hands were clean, they had still committed the sin, but preferring to ignore that fact. The one to die today had been trying to wrest power from one higher up in his qu’ellar. That meant nothing to Shaddowe, yet she would easily slit his throat without thinking twice, that was just the way it was. However, she took this mark eagerly for the iblith had dared to try to touch her, thinking that as a “lesser race” she would welcome his advances, or cower before him and allow him to take what he wished. Wael! She thought maliciously. Insulting me was the LAST thing you should have done. Not a sound was heard as she unstoppered a vial of deadly, painful poison and coated her blades. The door to the room was thick, and closed tightly. It would muffle any screams he might make, if she didn’t just cut his tongue out instead. Those victims who had not angered her, who were just a target to be eliminated met a quick, merciful death. This one would not be so lucky. 
<br />

<br />
She crept up behind the man, seated at the small desk in one corner of the dimly lit room. Tier’dal had little need for light unless reading, their vision was easily suited to see in the infrared spectrum, seeing the heat an object radiated clearly marking its place. Fier’dal vision was not nearly so advanced, but Shaddowe had come across an enchanted ring long before that allowed her to see as clearly as in the daytime, no matter how dark it was. The lack of challenge irritated her as she crept about halfway towards him, and she purposely misstepped, a floor board creaking and alerting him. He whirled about, a hidden dagger at the ready, and she laughed. Ah, now the hunt! As with many other fights, it was over too soon, the rogue on top of her mark, her hand over his mouth as her wicked dagger plunged deep into his belly. No fast clean end for this one…<br />_________________<br /><a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=738273" target="_blank" class="postlink"><img src="http://img.photobucket.com/albums/v701/evileene/evilsig2.jpg" border="0" /></a></span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
			</tr>
