			<tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">She spoke softly, just above a whisper, knowing that a whisper was actually more likely to be noticed. “And now you see, tier’dal, that it was a wood elf that spelled your end! You fell to one of the lesser races, naut at the hands of god or kin. What will Innoruuk think of you, wael? You have failed him!” When the man’s agonized groans grew annoying, she quickly slid her dagger into his heart, ending his life immediately. She wiped her daggers clean on her victims clothing, then quietly and efficiently ransacked his room, stealing all valuables, and a particular scroll of paper that Tani had asked her to watch for. As silently as she had entered, she now left, blending with the shadows once more on her way to the leader of the Ebon Mask. 
<br />

<br />
<span style="font-style: italic">Wandering deeper into the city, she left the loudness and bustle behind, happening upon another gate, and sneaking through it. Her eyes looked around this new area in awe, her mouth slightly open as she looked at the buildings and the water around them, magical symbols suspended in midair... This place was magical. She almost forgot herself and stepped out of the shadows, then shook her head, checking to see that her mask was still in place. Unlike the rest of Neriak, this place had a solemn, peaceful aura to it. Stopping to stare at a waterfall, with another symbol seemingly dangling in it, she decided she had found her place. If only she knew what it was called. </span>
<br />

<br />
The Third Gate was where she spent most of her time. It was the place she had claimed as her own on her first foray into Neriak and the one place where, even among allies, her presence was punishable by death. Thankfully, Tani did not share the religious convictions of his race, but she knew to always be cautious, for if she became a liability he could easily cite them as a reason for her elimination. Appearing boldly in the assassin’s guild hall, without her mask to disguise her, Shaddowe tossed the parchment and a few jewels at Tani’s feet. “It is done.” The guildmaster knew that what the fier’dal gave him was not all of what she had found there, but nothing was said. In return, he tossed a bag of coin her way. Catching it onehanded, she smirked and swaggered off. 
<br />

<br />
As she headed out of the protection of the Ebon Mask, she adjusted her mask upon her face yet again, its powerful majik transforming her features, and closed her eyes briefly, remembering the first time she had used it…</span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
			</tr>
