			<tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody"><span style="font-style: italic">Something bothered Shaddowe about the new rogue in V’Umbra… something that wasn’t precisely as it seemed. She wasn’t sure what part of her had seen it, but she wasn’t surprised. After all, like recognizes like, she too was a charlatan, a deceiver. She too pretended to be someone she was not. Perhaps the magical energies of the masks spoke to each other, for she somehow knew he wore one. His deception made her nervous, for she had known of it so easily. If he betrayed her, her new friends would kill her in a moment, she knew that. Was she strong enough to betray him first? The questions turned around in her mind, through her hunts with Leahali in the Overthere, and her forays about Highkeep and Neriak, never quite leaving her thoughts. The first confrontation was inevitable… 
<br />

<br />
“Who are you?” she murmured, barely looking at Gratis. “Why are you here?”</span> 
<br />

<br />
It hadn’t been the most auspicious beginning she thought. She had been insecure in her deception, he, almost arrogant in his. But distrust and dislike had blossomed into something more. She had been the first to break from the deception, giving up her badge quietly, and thinking to slip away, but he had found her. They had become friends and a bit more, but while he had encouraged her to give up her mask, he had refused to do the same. They had perhaps both had reasons to be unhappy in their own skin. The treatment of her own kind had left her scarred, feeling insignificant, unimportant. Only in this other form could she be beautiful in her own eyes, at that time. He was half tier’dal, half human, accepted in neither culture. Her mask gave her an identity, his gave him a home… 
<br />

<br />
<span style="font-style: italic">"Don't you know you are beautiful, Shaddowe? Why must you always hide behind that mask?" 
<br />

<br />
The tier'dal woman with startling raven hair laughingly whispered a few words and the spell of the enchanted mask faded, showing a young fier'dal with the same ebony hair, and eyes that constantly shifted color, depending on her mood and the lights. "This is ordinary, Gratis. Until I was able to become a tier'dal, no one saw me. I did not exist. Now I do. They think I'm beautiful. You think I'm beautiful." 
<br />

<br />
”I prefer you without. You must learn to feel comfortable in your own skin, to accept who you are, little rogue.” 
<br />

<br />
She turned on him, laughing incredulously. “Who are you to talk? You who I have only seen without his mask once! Even when we vith, you are naut yourself!” She had immersed herself in this culture, its language and euphemisms second nature to her now. It was a matter of survival, the tier’dal were quick to spot mistakes, and even faster to eliminate those who made them. She whispered the words to trigger the mask once more, then turned, inspecting her reflection in the room’s tarnished mirror. Shaddowe the wood elf was a mouse, quiet, shy, ultimately forgettable. Shaddowe the dark elf was a mynx, strong, independent, afraid of nothing. She had expected the mask to set her free, but she was still a prisoner of sorts, unable to be who she was inside unless she wore it. Gratis was the only one, she thought, who understood, the only one who would always be there. He found her beautiful, fascinating, even when she was only herself… </span></span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
