				<td colspan="2"><hr /></td>
			</tr>
			<tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">The erudite woman clad scantily in chain of the deepest violet turned heads as she walked through Freeport, head high and shoulders back. She had the air of arrogance that was usually expected from her race, one that prided itself on its intellect and looked down on most others. She noticed the stares and whispers, but did not react, as if she felt it beneath her to dignify those acts with a response. Her long strides quickly led her deep into the city. She wandered into the tunnels, a lawless place, seeming to not notice the dirt and squalor, and it was almost as if the filth of the place knew better than to touch her pristine chain skirt and boots. She stopped at the locked door of an office, near the tunnel entrance from the Freeport docks. A quick scan of the door, and her nimble fingers found and disarmed the trap there, picking the lock in a smooth, almost soundless, motion. The door swung open, the half elf inside sitting calm, his eyes on her, though she knew he had at least one dagger at the ready. She knew she had startled him, she could see it in his dilated pupils and the strange set of his shoulders, trying to look relaxed even while tensed at the ready. Only the most observant of strangers would have noticed this. What was most telling however, was something only those closest to him would realize… she was seeing him without his mask. 
<br />

<br />
“Your traps are getting better, shebali, but still naut enough to keep me out.” She moved into the room with a swagger, ruined by the giggle that escaped her. His shoulders had completely relaxed, as soon as he had heard her voice he knew there was no threat here. “Ah, Gratis… I have come to show you my new toy!” In the blink of an eye, a slight elf stood where the statuesque erudite had been, chocolate skin replaced by creamy pale, short curls growing long, lustrous and straight. The only thing the same were the ever-changing eyes and the aura of confidence. She tossed a mask at him, his quick reflexes allowing him to grab it without thinking. His stern face dissolved into a grin as he inspected the magical item. 
<br />

<br />
She had nursed her anger and her wounded pride for months, throwing herself into her training. Gratis had been the first lover she had had, and the first person she had opened herself to, and he had walked away. She quickly mastered the tasks and weapons her teachers set before her, working harder and learning faster than any other student of the Ebon Mask, and tested harder as well, after all, she was only fier’dal, she had to PROVE something to them, or why would they have her here. She took every assignment she was offered, no matter how foul or insulting. She killed people of all races, even her own. She learned to pick pockets with the best of the street trash, and to blend into the shadows with ease. She broke into rival qu’ellaren, stealing information, and to the government offices in Freeport and other cities, to plant evidence or spy. And slowly, she lost her dependence on the mask. She grew to see it as a crutch, and refused to use it, forcing herself to rely on her skill and her own inner strength, not a bit of enchanted leather…And then she met him again, for the first time on equal, if not superior, footing…<br />_________________<br /><a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=738273" target="_blank" class="postlink"><img src="http://img.photobucket.com/albums/v701/evileene/evilsig2.jpg" border="0" /></a></span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
			</tr>
