			<tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">“Vendui’ Gratis.” Her voice was calm, emotionless, giving nothing away to him. Her skin had grown paler, months of living in Neriak, keeping to the dark and the shadows, had stolen its tan glow. Her hair seemed even more impossibly dark, almost the color of a raven’s wing, braided loosely at the nape of her neck. Her relaxed pose didn’t hint at the knots in her stomach at the sight of him. 
<br />

<br />
He wore his mask, as always, all indigo skin, with unruly ivory locks. She could tell he too had been startled, but she knew that unlike him, none of her feelings showed on her face. His response was low, almost strained. “Vendui’ Shaddowe.” 
<br />

<br />
His voice could still send shivers down her spine, she noticed in one corner of her mind, but that first glow was gone. She no longer needed to fancy herself in love, or to dress it up. He had been her first, but no longer her only, and perhaps that confidence allowed her to do what came naturally, to boldly sit with him, drink with him, then take him to bed. 
<br />

<br />
When they came together it was passionate, explosive, intense, but never gentle. She never used the term lovemaking, but rather adopted the crude tier’dal term for intercourse. Vithing…that was all they did, all she could accept. She was usually the first to rise from the bed, to cloak herself in her clothing, she, who no longer had a shy bone in her body. Only then, away from the intimacy of the bed, and the stark honestly of nudity, could she open even a little bit, to be playful, even affectionate sometimes. Never there though, never where it might be confused for love…by either of them. She cared for him, as much as she could let herself, but it was always guarded and controlled. The logical part of her understood why he had left before. When she was discovered, she had earned the respect of much of Neriak already, had proven herself as an asset. He had not earned the same right. Even if he had done everything she had and more, his road would have still been harder than hers. She was an Other, but he was an abomination. The tier’dal prized their pure blood. Babes who were not full tier’dal were usually killed at birth, and those who grew to adulthood were often hunted with a fervor that surpassed their Hatred of the Lying Races. Half breeds were a mistake, an imperfection, and tier’dal were supposed to be perfect. Shaddowe had only ever met one other who had gained acceptance.<br />_________________<br /><a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=738273" target="_blank" class="postlink"><img src="http://img.photobucket.com/albums/v701/evileene/evilsig2.jpg" border="0" /></a></span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
