			<tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">She cloaked herself in shadow, or used her mask, whenever wandering the Third Gate. This place was the holiest of places in Neriak, forbidden for any not tier’dal to enter. This place was sacred to Innoruuk, and Shaddowe herself had seen him appear here once, hidden deep in the darkest recesses, when she was but a young student of Tani. She had watched him touch the one who was then Ilharn of DeVir, bestowing upon him new strength and power. She had watched other leaders of Neriak kneeling before the One they placed before all others, even themselves. In later days she had seen his Church turn on ones who had always been faithful, seemingly on a whim. She had watched child separated from mother, had seen one of the nobility struck down by his clergy, and her qu’ellar crumble to dust in the aftermath. The tier’dal claimed Innoruuk did not lie, but Shaddowe did not believe. 
<br />

<br />
Tunare, the Great Mother, the All-Mother, Goddess of Love. The assassin had even less respect for that one. Her followers preached love and acceptance, but Shaddowe had seen none of that growing up. Even the orphans of the tier’dal were better taken care of than she had been. Her sisters had been druids, like her mother, the closest the fier’dal had to clergy. Tunare had blessed them with powers she could not comprehend, those women who had ignored and neglected and belittled a child. What love was there? 
<br />

<br />
For every god or goddess the woman discovered, she also found more lies, more hypocrisy, more fools praying to a deity that turned a deaf ear. The more she saw of the gods, the more she hated them. An ironic voice in her head told her she was closest to Innoruuk now, the Prince of Hate, that her hate would make him glad, but she shrugged it off. For the first time, she had found an enemy that she could fight for the right reasons, not for money, not for acceptance, but for her own sense of justice. 
<br />

<br />
It’s impossible to kill a god, of course. If they could die, they wouldn’t be gods at all. But she had learned something. It was possible to kill their physical manifestation, to banish them from this existence for a time, how long or short depending completely on how powerful the god. And one could not kill a god alone. They were stronger than mere mortals, with armies at their commands, and powers that those who walked the land of Norrath could only imagine. And so Shaddowe went to war for the first time, invading the domains of her enemies, fighting side by side with other people, as she never had before in her life. Fighting in the light of day, and out of the shadows at last. 
<br />

<br />
She leaned back against the rock, watching the water fall seemingly out of the cavern ceiling, with no visible source. The all-seeing Eye of Innoruuk was suspended inside the flow, glowing brightly, and to the rogue, accusingly. The mist rose up around them, as the curtain of droplets isolated the pair from the rest of the Third Gate. Shadows of movement were visible past the deluge, but the two inside felt as isolated and private as if they were in their own room. She looked at her companion. What a pair they made, fier’dal and tier’dal. An assassin and a priestess. Yet they had been friends for so long.   She rolled over onto her stomach, shutting out the sight of the Eye, and focusing her attention on her companion. Indigo skin, lustrous long snowy locks, a trim form encased in crimson plate that had been molded close to her figure. Leahali had aged well, in the way of the tier’dal, barely looking a day older than when they had met. But in manner, the priestess had aged a hundred years. Far from the bubbly, giggling young cleric, Leah had come into her own. She was possessed of a wisdom and a grace often not found in jalilen two and three times her years. Shaddowe found her companionship rewarding, pleasing, and most of all, calming on her troubled spirit. Meeting Leah’s eyes, the assassin paused a moment, trying to find the words. Her mouth moved a few times, silently, then finally the words escaped. “Tell me what it is like, Leah…”</span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
