			<tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">The priestess looked at her questioningly, a smile quirking her full lips. Shaddowe often did this to her, pulled a question seemingly out of nowhere, forgetting for the moment that not all the world thought as she did. She waited for clarification. 
<br />

<br />
“Tell me what it’s like to have faith…” 
<br />

<br />
<span style="font-style: italic">She had met a guild of fighters, and had become friends with many of them, allying herself to their cause, and fighting by their side in many battles. The Sterling Order of Knights was a family as well as a guild, and they had accepted her presence among them easily, something she had never expected or hoped for. She was used to being the outsider. She followed them to Innoruuk’s domain more than once, the magics of the wizards mysteriously transporting them through time and place to a foreign world. She had fought by their side against creatures, the like of which she had never seen, as they worked their way through the eerie halls and cathedrals of the Hatred Plane…until the day when one of the scouts finally spotted Innoruuk himself in the throne room. Shaddowe scowled at just the thought of the Deity, and prepared herself to fight him, not even thinking of the possibility that they might lose the battle. She had more reason than this for being here though, reason that even these Knights did not know. 
<br />

<br />
In the heat of battle, she slipped away unnoticed, climbing a long winding ramp, following directions given to her long ago by one she had approached, after hearing of a mythical dagger. One of the clues to its existence was here, a Book of Souls hidden deep in the rooms of the Maestro of Rancor, one of Innoruuk’s chief lieutenants. She searched the dark and gloomy suite, finding the book she sought in plain sight on a desk. Concealing it beneath her armor, she rejoined the others. They had reached the Throne Room, and were waiting for the order to attack. Their leader Zantaer had gained the attention of the Prince of Hate’s minions, who had followed him out into ambush. Now the God stood alone. 
<br />

<br />
The barbarian warrior led the charge, singing songs of battle to his gods, as he gained the attention of the furious deity. As the healers stood back and prayed for their spells of healing, he let the monster back him into a corner, thinking it had the upper hand. “Attack!” was the call, and the rest of the Knights streamed into the room, surrounding Innoruuk and pushing him closer to the corner. Shaddowe’s first sight of Him had been horrific, in Neriak that day. Here, he was three times the size, huge and twisted and evil, and she felt the bloodrage pour through her body. His magic threw them all back into the walls, injuring many, but they all fought on, rushing back to hack and pierce at this physical manifestation of evil. “Kill this now!” the cry rang out, and the casters quickly summoned their most powerful spells against Him. When it was over, Shaddowe looked down at the remains of the God. She knew in her heart that it was not truly over, He was not truly dead, just banished for a time. But there was still satisfaction, a sense of accomplishment, of having fought a battle for the right reasons. Discussions of the treasures within the lair didn’t interest her, for her she had gotten what she had come for. She waited quietly in the corner, her heart beating in exhilaration, for the wizards to transport them home.</span><br />_________________<br /><a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=738273" target="_blank" class="postlink"><img src="http://img.photobucket.com/albums/v701/evileene/evilsig2.jpg" border="0" /></a></span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
