			<tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">The dagger gleamed brightly in the sunlight as it flashed up into the air, only to be caught by a dexterous hand. The hand was not delicate, it was calloused and strong from years of fighting and holding weapons, from climbing ropes and prying open locks. But it was beautiful, and graceful, and deadly. She ran a loving finger gently over the blade, careful not to cut herself, even years later, the edge stayed razor sharp. This dagger had been a legend, a myth told to her by a rogue guildleader in another town. She had chased rumors of it all over Norrath, and finally found one who would tell her more. Stanos Herkanor, the leader of the Highpass Smugglers, had known much of the dagger, but required Shaddowe’s assistance before he would tell her any more than she already knew. He had demanded that she bring him two pieces of parchment, that, once translated, would prove his innocence in a plot against one of his allies, he claimed. 
<br />

<br />
<span style="font-style: italic">“I entrusted one to Founy, but that trust is gone, and Founy would betray me to Hanns were I to attempt to reclaim it. Tani N’Mar has the other, which he should not possess, and keeps it only to spite me, not knowing its real import. Steal them both and bring them back to me.” 
<br />

<br />
Shaddowe had felt her stomach jump at the idea. To get this blade she had dreamed of, she must try to pick the pockets of the man who had taught her the art. It would require nerves of steel, at the least. At the most, it would also require a healthy dose of luck. She could give up, she supposed, and just forget her vision of being the one to wield this weapon. A small smile played about her lips. This was one rogue who did not give up easily. 
<br />

<br />
She had gone back to Tani, asking for more training in the art of poison-making. As she worked side by side with him in the lab, she found many ways to “brush” against him as they mixed components and filled vials. At the end of their hours together, she would go through her pockets, checking to see what she had gathered. She had replaced all the coin as she went, hoping it would be less noticeable. On the third day, she left the lab, tired and discouraged, only to find she finally had what she had been looking for: a parchment in an unknown language, stained and yellowed with age, with a jagged tear along the top. This was it! 
<br />

<br />
Founy had been easier for her. She had simply stayed to the shadows, sneaking behind the dwarf. It had taken two attempts for her questing fingers to find the parchment, and then she ran for the entrance to the city, and the safety of the Butcherblock Mountains. Unfortunately, she had soon learned that wasn’t the only task between her and the dagger. 
<br />

<br />
The little gnome, Yendar Starpyre, had told her he needed a book from Innoruuk’s Domain. The Book of Souls, a catalogue of all the souls Innoruuk had twisted over his reign, was kept deep in the Plane of Hate by the Maestro of Rancor. Shaddowe was easily able to attain that, using the attack on Hate and the chaos of the fight to cover up what she was after. He had used the book to translate the parchments. She had had to fight to get the parchments from another assassin who had come by and stolen them, but she won. But even that was not enough for Stanos…</span><br />_________________<br /><a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=738273" target="_blank" class="postlink"><img src="http://img.photobucket.com/albums/v701/evileene/evilsig2.jpg" border="0" /></a></span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
